Paul Weeks (pictured) boarded the routine passenger flight on March 8, 2014. Mrs Weeks has revealed  the agony of constantly wondering what happened to him

On March 8, 2014, 39-year-old Paul Weeks boarded seat 1C, business class, on the routine passenger flight which departed from Kuala Lumpur and was bound for Beijing.

The 40-year-old-mother will describe the agony of constantly wondering what happened to him on the program.

She's frustrated with Malaysian authorities, claiming they've simply refused to answer her questions.

'They just won't tell us. I can only hope we get something, anything,' she says while fighting back tears in a trailer for the program. 

'They are wanting to put this aside. In their own words - to move beyond MH370. How do you move? We don't get to move beyond! We will never get to move beyond. So how can they just move beyond this and forget about it?' 

The program will also tracks the developments, false alarms and disappointments in the year-long hunt for MH370 through Mrs Weeks's eyes.

Despite the most expensive search and rescue operation in history, not a single trace of the plane, or its passengers and crew has been found. 

